{
    "title": "diff segment from contiguos",
    "html": "<div class=\"markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark\"><p data-start=\"0\" data-end=\"171\" class=\"\">The key difference between <strong data-start=\"27\" data-end=\"43\">segmentation</strong> and <strong data-start=\"48\" data-end=\"80\">contiguous memory allocation</strong> lies in how the memory is divided and assigned to a process. Let me break it down clearly:</p>\n<hr data-start=\"173\" data-end=\"176\" class=\"\">\n<h3 data-start=\"178\" data-end=\"217\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"182\" data-end=\"217\">1. Contiguous Memory Allocation</strong></h3>\n<ul data-start=\"218\" data-end=\"566\">\n<li data-start=\"218\" data-end=\"288\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"220\" data-end=\"288\" class=\"\">Each process gets <strong data-start=\"238\" data-end=\"277\">one continuous (single block) chunk</strong> of memory.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"289\" data-end=\"369\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"291\" data-end=\"369\" class=\"\">The <strong data-start=\"295\" data-end=\"311\">base address</strong> is fixed, and memory is accessed using <strong data-start=\"351\" data-end=\"368\">Base + Offset</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"370\" data-end=\"426\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"372\" data-end=\"426\" class=\"\">The entire process must fit into <strong data-start=\"405\" data-end=\"425\">one single chunk</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"427\" data-end=\"566\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"429\" data-end=\"566\" class=\"\">If thereâ€™s enough free memory but itâ€™s fragmented (not continuous), the process <strong data-start=\"509\" data-end=\"539\">cannot be allocated memory</strong> unless compaction is done.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"568\" data-end=\"809\" class=\"\">âœ… <strong data-start=\"570\" data-end=\"582\">Example:</strong><br data-start=\"582\" data-end=\"585\">\nLet's say we have <strong data-start=\"603\" data-end=\"618\">400 KB free</strong>, but it's split into <strong data-start=\"640\" data-end=\"694\">100 KB + 150 KB + 150 KB (scattered across memory)</strong>.<br data-start=\"695\" data-end=\"698\">\nIf a process needs <strong data-start=\"717\" data-end=\"727\">300 KB</strong>, it <strong data-start=\"732\" data-end=\"755\">cannot be allocated</strong> because thereâ€™s no single continuous block of 300 KB.</p>\n<p data-start=\"811\" data-end=\"923\" class=\"\">ðŸ”´ <strong data-start=\"814\" data-end=\"839\">Why is it contiguous?</strong><br data-start=\"839\" data-end=\"842\">\nBecause the whole process must be loaded into <strong data-start=\"888\" data-end=\"895\">one</strong> continuous block of memory.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"925\" data-end=\"928\" class=\"\">\n<h3 data-start=\"930\" data-end=\"953\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"934\" data-end=\"953\">2. Segmentation</strong></h3>\n<ul data-start=\"954\" data-end=\"1295\">\n<li data-start=\"954\" data-end=\"1077\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"956\" data-end=\"1077\" class=\"\">Instead of giving the process <strong data-start=\"986\" data-end=\"1010\">one continuous chunk</strong>, we divide it into <strong data-start=\"1030\" data-end=\"1050\">logical segments</strong> (Code, Stack, Heap, Data).</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1078\" data-end=\"1135\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1080\" data-end=\"1135\" class=\"\">Each <strong data-start=\"1085\" data-end=\"1134\">segment gets its own independent base address</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1136\" data-end=\"1237\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1138\" data-end=\"1237\" class=\"\">Memory is <strong data-start=\"1148\" data-end=\"1181\">not required to be contiguous</strong>; segments can be scattered across the available memory.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1238\" data-end=\"1295\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1240\" data-end=\"1295\" class=\"\">The segment number helps find the correct base address.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"1297\" data-end=\"1357\" class=\"\">âœ… <strong data-start=\"1299\" data-end=\"1311\">Example:</strong><br data-start=\"1311\" data-end=\"1314\">\nLet's say we need to load a process with:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1358\" data-end=\"1419\">\n<li data-start=\"1358\" data-end=\"1377\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1360\" data-end=\"1377\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1360\" data-end=\"1377\">Code (120 KB)</strong></p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1378\" data-end=\"1397\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1380\" data-end=\"1397\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1380\" data-end=\"1397\">Heap (100 KB)</strong></p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1398\" data-end=\"1419\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1400\" data-end=\"1419\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1400\" data-end=\"1417\">Stack (80 KB)</strong></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"1421\" data-end=\"1486\" class=\"\">We <strong data-start=\"1424\" data-end=\"1452\">donâ€™t need one big block</strong> of 300 KB. Instead, we can place:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1487\" data-end=\"1581\">\n<li data-start=\"1487\" data-end=\"1514\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1489\" data-end=\"1514\" class=\"\">Code in one 120 KB block.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1515\" data-end=\"1549\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1517\" data-end=\"1549\" class=\"\">Heap in a separate 100 KB block.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1550\" data-end=\"1581\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"1552\" data-end=\"1581\" class=\"\">Stack in another 80 KB block.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"1583\" data-end=\"1750\" class=\"\">ðŸ”µ <strong data-start=\"1586\" data-end=\"1615\">Why is it non-contiguous?</strong><br data-start=\"1615\" data-end=\"1618\">\nBecause different <strong data-start=\"1636\" data-end=\"1648\">segments</strong> of the same process can be stored in <strong data-start=\"1686\" data-end=\"1709\">different locations</strong> in memory, unlike contiguous allocation.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1752\" data-end=\"1755\" class=\"\">\n<h3 data-start=\"1757\" data-end=\"1780\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"1761\" data-end=\"1780\">Key Differences</strong></h3>\n<div class=\"overflow-x-auto contain-inline-size\"><table data-start=\"1781\" data-end=\"2574\" node=\"[object Object]\"><thead data-start=\"1781\" data-end=\"1839\"><tr data-start=\"1781\" data-end=\"1839\"><th data-start=\"1781\" data-end=\"1791\">Feature</th><th data-start=\"1791\" data-end=\"1819\"><strong data-start=\"1793\" data-end=\"1818\">Contiguous Allocation</strong></th><th data-start=\"1819\" data-end=\"1839\"><strong data-start=\"1821\" data-end=\"1837\">Segmentation</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody data-start=\"1897\" data-end=\"2574\"><tr data-start=\"1897\" data-end=\"1988\"><td><strong data-start=\"1899\" data-end=\"1920\">Memory Assignment</strong></td><td>One continuous block</td><td>Divided into segments, stored separately</td></tr><tr data-start=\"1989\" data-end=\"2112\"><td><strong data-start=\"1991\" data-end=\"2008\">Fragmentation</strong></td><td>Suffers from <strong data-start=\"2024\" data-end=\"2050\">external fragmentation</strong></td><td>Suffers from <strong data-start=\"2066\" data-end=\"2092\">external fragmentation</strong> but more flexible</td></tr><tr data-start=\"2113\" data-end=\"2215\"><td><strong data-start=\"2115\" data-end=\"2133\">Base + Offset?</strong></td><td>Yes, single base address</td><td>Yes, but multiple base addresses (one per segment)</td></tr><tr data-start=\"2216\" data-end=\"2316\"><td><strong data-start=\"2218\" data-end=\"2233\">Flexibility</strong></td><td>Low, needs memory compaction</td><td>High, logical segments can be placed separately</td></tr><tr data-start=\"2317\" data-end=\"2448\"><td><strong data-start=\"2319\" data-end=\"2340\">Memory Efficiency</strong></td><td>Wastes memory due to external fragmentation</td><td>More efficient, since segments can fit in separate spaces</td></tr><tr data-start=\"2449\" data-end=\"2574\"><td><strong data-start=\"2451\" data-end=\"2466\">Example Use</strong></td><td>Simple memory allocation systems (old OS)</td><td>Used in architectures like x86 (stack, heap, code segments)</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<hr data-start=\"2576\" data-end=\"2579\" class=\"\">\n<h3 data-start=\"2581\" data-end=\"2608\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"2585\" data-end=\"2608\">Final Understanding</strong></h3>\n<p data-start=\"2609\" data-end=\"2710\" class=\"\">Even though segmentation still uses <strong data-start=\"2645\" data-end=\"2662\">Base + Offset</strong>, it differs from contiguous allocation because:</p>\n<ol data-start=\"2711\" data-end=\"2926\">\n<li data-start=\"2711\" data-end=\"2795\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"2714\" data-end=\"2795\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"2714\" data-end=\"2747\">Each segment has its own base</strong> instead of a single base for the whole process.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2796\" data-end=\"2926\" class=\"\">\n<p data-start=\"2799\" data-end=\"2926\" class=\"\"><strong data-start=\"2799\" data-end=\"2855\">Segments can be placed in different memory locations</strong>, unlike contiguous allocation, where the process must be in one block.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p data-start=\"2928\" data-end=\"2960\" class=\"\">Would a diagram help clarify? ðŸš€</p></div>"
